# Phase 5 – Real Data Engineering

---

# First — What Problem Does Incremental Loading Solve?

Suppose at Amazon:

## orders table

Contains:

* 5 billion rows

Every hour new data arrives:

* only 10,000 rows changed

Bad approach:

```text id="s4m8qx"
Reload all 5 billion rows
```

Huge waste.

Incremental loading solves this.

---

# What is Incremental Loading?

## Theory

**Incremental Loading** is a process where only new or changed data is loaded into the target system instead of reloading the entire dataset.

---

# Simple Definition

Load only delta changes.

---

# Important Insight ⭐

Incremental loading depends heavily on:

* CDC
* timestamps
* version tracking
* primary keys

This is why CDC topic came first.

---

# Full Load vs Incremental Load ⭐⭐⭐

| Full Load         | Incremental Load  |
| ----------------- | ----------------- |
| Reload everything | Load only changes |
| Expensive         | Efficient         |
| Slow              | Faster            |
| Heavy compute     | Lower cost        |
| Simple logic      | More complex      |

---

# Real Example

## Source Table

| order_id | amount | updated_at |
| -------- | ------ | ---------- |
| 101      | 500    | 10:00      |
| 102      | 700    | 10:05      |

---

# ETL Run at 10:10

Stores:

```text id="g7p2vn"
last_run_time = 10:10
```

---

# Next ETL Run

Query:

```sql id="y4t8kr"
SELECT *
FROM orders
WHERE updated_at > '10:10';
```

Only new/changed rows loaded.

That is incremental loading.

