# Common Incremental Strategies ⭐

# 1. Timestamp-Based Incremental Loading

Most common.

---

# Logic

Load rows where:

```sql id="r2x6pm"
updated_at > last_run_time
```

---

# Advantages

* simple
* easy implementation

---

# Problems ⚠️

* clock synchronization issues
* missed late records
* delete handling difficult

---

# 2. CDC-Based Incremental Loading ⭐⭐⭐

CDC detects:

* insert
* update
* delete

Pipeline incrementally processes changes.

Most enterprise-grade approach.

---

# Example Flow

```text id="n8w4zc"
Database Logs
      |
     CDC
      |
Incremental ETL
      |
Warehouse
```

---

# 3. Batch Incremental Loading

Runs periodically:

* hourly
* daily
* every 15 minutes

Most common enterprise pattern.

---

# 4. Streaming Incremental Loading

Near real-time continuous ingestion.

Used in:

* Kafka pipelines
* event systems
* streaming analytics

Advanced architecture.

---

# Important ETL Concepts ⭐

# Append Strategy

Only new rows inserted.

Example:

* logs
* transactions

---

# Merge / Upsert Strategy ⭐

Update existing rows if record exists.

Insert if new.

Very important warehouse pattern.

---

# Example

```text id="k3m9qa"
If customer exists -> UPDATE
Else -> INSERT
```

---

# SQL-Style Merge Example

```sql id="u6v1pt"
MERGE INTO dim_customer t
USING staging_customer s
ON t.customer_id = s.customer_id
WHEN MATCHED THEN UPDATE
WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN INSERT;
```

Very common DE interview pattern.

---

# Watermark Concept ⭐⭐⭐

One of the most important incremental load concepts.

---

# What is Watermark?

Stores latest successfully processed value.

Example:

```text id="d5r8xy"
last_processed_timestamp = 2026-01-10 10:00
```

Next ETL starts after this point.

---

# Why Watermark Important?

Prevents:

* duplicate loads
* missed records
* reprocessing issues

---

# Late Arriving Data Problem ⚠️

Suppose:

* record created at 10:05
* arrives at 11:00

Simple timestamp logic may miss it.

Huge real-world problem.

We’ll cover later.

---

# Incremental Load + SCD Connection ⭐

Incremental pipeline detects changed dimension row.

Then:

* SCD Type 1 → overwrite
* SCD Type 2 → insert historical version

This is actual warehouse ETL flow.

---

# Real Warehouse Example

At Netflix:

Watch events continuously arrive.

Incremental loading processes:

* only new watch events
* not entire history daily

